As this has been done with the ABS brake blocking system and as this will be done with the ESP stability control, emergency braking support systems will be a mandatory element on European cars.
They are already mandatory on newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest of the vehicles a period of shortage has been fixed until the end of February 2011.
The measure imposed by the European Union is aimed at strengthening pedestrian protection, even if, by its mode of action, it can also help to avoid many rear shocks.
The emergency braking assistant acts by increasing the pressure on the brakes in case of emergency detected by the system by means of the driver's kick.
But the latter doesn't always keep the pressure until the end.
According to a study conducted by the manufacturer of components for Bosch cars, one third of the drivers involved in an accident could not support the brake before collision, and half of them had not benefited from all its strength.
Up to 1 100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, on the other hand, requires the maximum brake system, reducing the distance the car needs to stop.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with this type of item, up to 1 100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided every year.
This reduction would be even more important with the popularization of these intelligent emergency braking systems: it is estimated that a disaster on four with injuries would be avoided.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that, thanks to a radar or a camera, detects the obstacles and prevents the driver, in addition to slightly acting on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, he helps by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
If it does not react, and although collision is inevitable, the device exerts maximum effort on brakes to minimize damage.
